example.p:
We will demonstrate that

\vect{v}=\colvector{-1\\2\\3\\-1\\4}

is an unobtainable element of the codomain.  Suppose to the contrary that $\vect{u}$ is an element of the domain such that $\lt{T}{\vect{u}}=\vect{v}$.

subsection.p:
Here's a cartoon of a non-surjective linear transformation.  Notice that the central feature of this cartoon is that the vector $\vect{v}\in V$ does not have an arrow pointing to it, implying there is no $\vect{u}\in U$ such that $\lt{T}{\vect{u}}=\vect{v}$.  Even though this happens again with a second unnamed vector in $V$, it only takes one occurrence to destroy the possibility of surjectivity.

